{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"11ceef6e-5cdd-4f33-9baa-0ed964c020cd","content":"In .NET 10, `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` was replaced with a **cross-platform** `Page.SafeAreaRegions` property.\n\n**Old (.NET 9):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"\n    ...>\n```\n\n**New (.NET 10):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    SafeAreaRegions=\"All\"\n    ...>\n```\n\nYou can drop the `xmlns:ios` namespace entirely if that was its only use. The new property also gives you granular control with flag values: `None`, `Top`, `Bottom`, `Left`, `Right`, or combinations like `\"Top,Bottom\"`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4ae8735d-72a0-459a-8c5c-660b3e31ba21","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI migration issue from .NET 9 to .NET 10 regarding safe area handling on iOS. This is a known breaking change in .NET MAUI.\n\nIn .NET 10 (specifically MAUI), the `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` attached property was removed/deprecated. The replacement is to use the new `SafeAreaRegions` property on `Page`.\n\nLet me provide the correct answer based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI changes.\n\nIn .NET 10, `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` was replaced with a cross-platform `Page.SafeAreaRegions` property. \n\nThe new `SafeAreaRegions` enum provides more granular control with options like `None` for no padding, `All` for safe area on all sides (the default), and individual flags for `Top`, `Bottom`, `Left`, and `Right` that can be combined. The old iOS-specific XML namespace approach has been replaced with this simpler cross-platform property.","outputTokens":559,"requestId":"9435:353499:1390EC1:15E8F6A:6A066E7C"},"id":"9590f0e3-5978-4ee9-860b-96cc4370eeae","timestamp":"2026-05-15T00:53:26.891Z","parentId":"95ad85d6-5578-4a9f-961d-7e76b9ec0aa9"}
